    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_40760976" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/40760976" />
    <a title="Crank" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/91946-crank"><img alt="Crank" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1230073329p2/91946.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/40760976?book_show_action=true">Dec 23, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Crank" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Crank" href="/user/show/91946-crank">Crank</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer40760976" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13660290517621219358">Tom Friedman applies his knowledge of the IT revolution and Middle Eastern petropolitics to the emerging world of cleantech, or, as he likes to call it, Energy Technology (ET). If you&apos;ve been reading his columns since &quot;The World is Flat&quot; there isn&apos;t much new here, but he does synthesize it all very well. Each chapter is like a very long, well-reasoned op-ed, full of name dropping, matter-of-fact observation and trend spotting, which can really be read in any order.</span>
  <span id="freeText13660290517621219358" style="display:none">Tom Friedman applies his knowledge of the IT revolution and Middle Eastern petropolitics to the emerging world of cleantech, or, as he likes to call it, Energy Technology (ET). If you've been reading his columns since "The World is Flat" there isn't much new here, but he does synthesize it all very well. Each chapter is like a very long, well-reasoned op-ed, full of name dropping, matter-of-fact observation and trend spotting, which can really be read in any order.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13660290517621219358" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


